00:00:05.479 --> 00:00:07.020
DINA WEISBERGER:
I'm Dina Weisberger.

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:08.700
PETER DOLCHIN: And
I'm Peter Dolchin.

00:00:08.700 --> 00:00:11.340
We're both from the Global
Partnerships group on the Telco

00:00:11.340 --> 00:00:14.395
and Video Distributors team.

00:00:14.395 --> 00:00:16.020
DINA WEISBERGER: We'd
like to thank you

00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:17.936
for taking the time out
of your busy schedules

00:00:17.936 --> 00:00:19.330
to join us today.

00:00:19.330 --> 00:00:21.720
Our talk is about
destigmatizing suicide.

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:23.920
And as someone recently
affected by it,

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.150
I learned, while it might be
a hard subject to navigate,

00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:30.210
it is also crucial we bring this
topic from out of the shadows

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:32.189
and into the light.

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:35.850
The goal today and for future
Talks at Google on suicide

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:38.370
is to raise awareness
surrounding mental illness

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:40.620
and help create a space
for those affected

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.390
by it to feel supported.

00:00:42.390 --> 00:00:46.500
So thank you for showing up
and demonstrating your support.

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.170
We and Nicole are on
a mission to change

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:52.440
the public perception of
suicide by eliminating

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:54.019
the silence around it.

00:00:54.019 --> 00:00:55.560
We believe one of
the best ways to do

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:58.800
this is to connect a real
beloved person to a deeply

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:03.210
stigmatized word, suicide,
through stories and images.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:05.820
Before Nicole talks about
losing her daughter, Dominique,

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:08.070
to suicide, she'll
share a brief montage.

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:13.680
While this may be an emotionally
evocative experience for many

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:16.440
of you, we hope that it
empowers those of you who

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:18.840
are suffering to reach out
for help, and for those

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:22.200
who know a loved one who is
struggling to approach them.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:24.660
With that said, we wanted to
highlight the mental health

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:27.720
resources available
at Google and beyond.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:30.600
Because the topic of suicide
is not one to be taken lightly,

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:34.470
we want to encourage anyone with
suicidal thoughts who are just

00:01:34.470 --> 00:01:37.020
looking for someone to talk
to to please reach out to one

00:01:37.020 --> 00:01:39.000
of the resources listed here--

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.660
the National Suicide Prevention
Hotline, the Crisis Text Line,

00:01:42.660 --> 00:01:45.090
and the American Foundation
for Suicide Prevention which

00:01:45.090 --> 00:01:47.460
you can just find support.

00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:49.667
There are biological and
psychological treatments

00:01:49.667 --> 00:01:51.750
that can help you address
underlying mental health

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:53.850
issues leading to suicide,
and we want everyone

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:55.530
to know there is a path forward.

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:57.300
Thank you.

00:01:57.300 --> 00:01:58.530
PETER DOLCHIN: Thanks, Dina.

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:01.110
